Update all UI components to use the implemented hooks instead of mock data. Add loading states and error handling to provide a smooth user experience.

Implementation steps:
1. Identify all components using mock data
2. Replace mock data with hook calls
3. Add loading states (skeletons, spinners)
4. Add error handling and fallbacks
5. Ensure UI remains consistent

Example for Tasks page:
```typescript
// src/pages/TasksPage.tsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import { useTasks } from '../hooks/useTasks';
import { TaskList, TaskForm, ErrorMessage, LoadingSpinner } from '../components';

const TasksPage = () => {
  const [selectedTaskId, setSelectedTaskId] = useState(null);
  const { getTasks, createTask, updateTask, deleteTask } = useTasks();
  const { data: tasks, isLoading, error } = getTasks;

  const handleCreateTask = (taskData) => {
    createTask.mutate(taskData);
  };

  const handleUpdateTask = (id, data) => {
    updateTask.mutate({ id, data });
  };

  const handleDeleteTask = (id) => {
    deleteTask.mutate(id);
  };

  if (isLoading) return <LoadingSpinner />;
  if (error) return <ErrorMessage message="Failed to load tasks" />;

  return (
    <div className="tasks-page">
      <h1>Tasks</h1>
      <TaskForm 
        onSubmit={handleCreateTask} 
        isLoading={createTask.isLoading}
      />
      <TaskList 
        tasks={tasks} 
        onUpdate={handleUpdateTask}
        onDelete={handleDeleteTask}
        onSelect={setSelectedTaskId}
        selectedTaskId={selectedTaskId}
        isUpdating={updateTask.isLoading}
        isDeleting={deleteTask.isLoading}
      />
    </div>
  );
};

export default TasksPage;
```

Implement a standardized approach to handling API errors and displaying loading states throughout the application. This will provide a consistent user experience and make debugging easier.

Implementation steps:
1. Create reusable error handling utilities
2. Create reusable loading components (skeletons, spinners)
3. Implement global error handling for API requests
4. Add retry mechanisms for failed requests
5. Create user-friendly error messages

```typescript
// src/utils/errorHandling.ts
export const formatApiError = (error) => {
  if (error.response) {
    // The request was made and the server responded with an error status
    return {
      message: error.response.data.message || 'Server error',
      status: error.response.status,
      details: error.response.data,
    };
  } else if (error.request) {
    // The request was made but no response was received
    return {
      message: 'No response from server',
      status: 0,
      details: { request: error.request },
    };
  } else {
    // Something happened in setting up the request
    return {
      message: error.message || 'Unknown error',
      status: 0,
      details: error,
    };
  }
};

// src/components/ErrorFallback.tsx
import React from 'react';

interface ErrorFallbackProps {
  error: any;
  resetErrorBoundary?: () => void;
}

export const ErrorFallback: React.FC<ErrorFallbackProps> = ({ 
  error, 
  resetErrorBoundary 
}) => {
  return (
    <div className="error-fallback">
      <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
      <p>{error.message || 'Unknown error'}</p>
      {resetErrorBoundary && (
        <button onClick={resetErrorBoundary}>Try again</button>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};

// src/components/LoadingSpinner.tsx
import React from 'react';

interface LoadingSpinnerProps {
  size?: 'small' | 'medium' | 'large';
  message?: string;
}

export const LoadingSpinner: React.FC<LoadingSpinnerProps> = ({ 
  size = 'medium', 
  message = 'Loading...' 
}) => {
  return (
    <div className={`loading-spinner loading-spinner--${size}`}>
      <div className="spinner"></div>
      {message && <p>{message}</p>}
    </div>
  );
};
```

This task focuses on improving the TypeScript implementation in our custom hooks to ensure type safety and proper React Hook usage.

Implementation steps:

1. Create proper TypeScript interfaces for API request/response data:
   - Define interfaces for all API responses in separate type definition files
   - Create request parameter interfaces for all API calls
   - Organize types by service/domain

```typescript
// src/types/api/tasks.ts
export interface Task {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  description: string;
  status: 'todo' | 'in_progress' | 'done';
  priority: 'low' | 'medium' | 'high';
  dueDate?: string;
  createdAt: string;
  updatedAt: string;
}

export interface TasksResponse {
  tasks: Task[];
  pagination: {
    total: number;
    page: number;
    limit: number;
  };
}

export interface CreateTaskRequest {
  title: string;
  description: string;
  priority: 'low' | 'medium' | 'high';
  dueDate?: string;
}
```

2. Update all custom hooks to use the new interfaces:
   - Replace all 'any' types with proper interfaces
   - Add proper return type definitions for all hooks
   - Add proper parameter type definitions

```typescript
// Before
const useTasks = (filters: any) => {
  // implementation
  return { tasks: data as any, isLoading, error };
};

// After
const useTasks = (filters: TaskFilters): UseTasksResult => {
  // implementation
  return { tasks: data as TasksResponse, isLoading, error };
};
```

3. Fix React Hook rules violations:
   - Identify instances where useQuery is called inside functions that aren't React components or custom hooks
   - Refactor code to ensure hooks are only called at the top level of components or custom hooks
   - Move hook calls outside of conditional blocks or loops

```typescript
// Before - Violation: hook inside regular function
const getTaskData = (id: string) => {
  const { data } = useQuery(['task', id], () => fetchTask(id));
  return data;
};

// After - Fixed: moved to proper custom hook
const useTaskData = (id: string) => {
  const { data } = useQuery(['task', id], () => fetchTask(id));
  return data;
};
```

4. Add proper error handling with typed error responses:
   - Create error type definitions
   - Update error handling to use typed errors
   - Ensure consistent error handling across hooks

5. Update all hooks to follow the same pattern:
   - Consistent naming conventions
   - Consistent parameter and return types
   - Consistent error handling
   - Consistent loading state handling

6. Update the following hooks with proper TypeScript types:
   - useChat
   - useTasks
   - useDayLogs
   - useAiService
   - useJobMetrics
   - Any other custom hooks in the codebase

tasks.testStrategy:
1. Run TypeScript compiler in strict mode to verify all type errors are resolved:
   ```bash
   npx tsc --noEmit --strict
   ```

2. Run ESLint with React Hooks plugin to verify all hook rules are followed:
   ```bash
   npx eslint --ext .ts,.tsx src/hooks/
   ```

3. Write unit tests for each updated hook to verify they work with the new type definitions:
   ```typescript
   // src/hooks/useTasks.test.ts
   import { renderHook } from '@testing-library/react-hooks';
   import { useTasks } from './useTasks';

   test('useTasks returns properly typed data', async () => {
     const { result, waitForNextUpdate } = renderHook(() => 
       useTasks({ status: 'todo' })
     );

     await waitForNextUpdate();

     // Type checking should pass
     const { tasks } = result.current;
     expect(tasks.pagination.total).toBeNumber();
     expect(tasks.tasks[0].id).toBeString();
   });
   ```

4. Test each hook with mock data that matches the new interfaces to ensure compatibility.

5. Verify that all components using these hooks still work correctly after the changes.

6. Create integration tests that use the hooks in components to verify end-to-end functionality.

7. Test error scenarios to ensure typed error handling works correctly:
   ```typescript
   test('useTasks handles errors with proper typing', async () => {
     // Mock API to return error
     server.use(
       rest.get('/api/tasks', (req, res, ctx) => {
         return res(ctx.status(500), ctx.json({ message: 'Server error' }));
       })
     );

     const { result, waitForNextUpdate } = renderHook(() => useTasks({}));

     await waitForNextUpdate();

     expect(result.current.error).toHaveProperty('message');
     expect(result.current.error.message).toBe('Server error');
   });
   ```

8. Run a full regression test suite to ensure no functionality was broken by the type changes.

